  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony in the United States and in many other jurisdictions around the world. Money laundering involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\"). This typically involves a series of transactions designed to obscure the origin of the money.\n\nIn the United States, money laundering is punishable under several federal statutes, including the **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)**, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986**, and the **Patriot Act**. Penalties for money laundering can be severe, including:\n\n- **Fines**: Significant monetary penalties, which can be up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction, whichever is greater.\n- **Imprisonment**: Felony convictions can result in prison sentences ranging from several years to up to 20 years per count, depending on the specifics of the case.\n- **Asset Forfeiture**: The government can seize property and assets involved in or traceable to the money laundering activity.\n\nMoreover, individuals and organizations involved in money laundering may also face additional charges, such as conspiracy, fraud, or racketeering, which can carry their own separate penalties.\n\nIt's important to consult with a legal professional if you are dealing with issues related to money laundering or if you have been accused of such activity.",
